==<span style="color:#fff212;">Description</span>==
{{blurimage|file=twister3.jpg|caption=First image taken of Level 142. Photographer status deceased.|align=right}}
<span style="color:#ed3237;">'''"<span style="color:#fff212;">Left Hand</span><span style="color:#00afef;"> Blue'''</span>,<span style="color:#ed3237;">"</span> otherwise known as <span style="color:#ed3237;">Level 142</span>, takes the appearance of a brightly lit game room themed entirely around the children's game Twister. The level resembles a four-walled square room that features smooth walls and ceilings made of white, fluorescent ceiling panels. All of the available surfaces, including the floor, the walls, and the ceiling are covered with painted multi-colored dots. 

On one of the sides of the room, there is a spinner resembling the conventional Twister spinner, which works without any means and does not have any apparent mechanical or electrical source of energy. The spinner gives out an almost mechanical click, whether it is spinning or not, while when spinning, it gives out instructions by means of a disembodied voice of a cheerfully optimistic and enthusiastic individual who seems to belong to some old-fashioned game shows in 1970s America. 

The room is exceptionally clean, as there are no dust traces, stains, or indications of age in the room. Regardless of how long the match lasts or the physical exertion experienced, all the evidence of sweating or dirt from the body disappears when the level is reset.

<span style="color:#00a859;">Level 142</span> is inactive until at least two wanderers occupy the level. If there is only one wanderer in the level, the spinner will be inactive while the room itself is passive. During this inactive state, the usual needs such as hunger, thirst, and fatigue operate normally. Some wanderers reported they had to wait for days or even weeks alone within the level for others to join. There are many accounts of wanting human company despite knowing the repercussions of starting the game. <span style="color:#FFFFFF;">When activation conditions are met, the level launches a series of automatic matches. 

The players have to position themselves according to the instructions provided by the spinner. Unlike in the original game, failing to follow the spinner's instructions does not necessarily mean falling down; the refusal to comply and improper positioning also serve as conditions of failure. Wanderers can talk throughout the matches, and communication between the participants is characteristic of the level's psychological pressure.

The perception of time in <span style="color:#00afef;">Level 142</span> is severely distorted. While playing, twenty-minute matches may feel like several days in reality. Moreover, while playing the game actively, wanderers do not experience hunger or thirst. 

As the match advances to higher stages, the behavior of the spinner will start to alter. Instructions will tend to become faster, more repetitive, and sometimes even contradictory. The voice gradually changes from the cheerful one at the onset of play into an erratic and unstable one. Commands seem to predict motions before the spinner makes a full spin, indicating a form of predictability or bias on the part of the instructions. 
{{blurimage|file=twister2.jpg|caption=Second image taken of Level 142. Photographer status alive.|align=center}}
This is often called "spinner cheating" among victims of the game, despite no mechanism being known for such a process. 

In the course of high-stakes matches, wanderers experience various forms of perceptual distortion. Circles have been found to duplicate, move slightly, and even alter in temperature. Correct circles become warmer and stable to place on, while incorrect or forbidden circles feel cold and slippery. In severe levels of exhaustion, wanderers have reported sensing imaginary circles that cannot be seen and receiving incorrect instructions and circle colors.

<span style="color:#FFFFFF;">Should one fail at any qualifying condition, the wanderer will be instantly no-clipped into a dangerous level of the Backrooms and will lose both hands and feet as punishment. The limbs in question have been neatly sealed and cauterized, with no trace of blood loss or further physical injuries being visible. Wanderers have testified to constant phantom limb pain whenever their minds were subjected to stress.

The role of <span style="color:#00a859;">Level 142</span> seems to have an evaluative purpose. In essence, this level is designed as an endurance test for the wanderer, with particular emphasis placed on the subject's coordination skills and mental fortitude. The intelligence behind this level remains unknown. </span><div class="darkblock">'''Please read aloud the numbers that you can see and mentally store the numbers that you cannot see.''' Do not speculate. Should a certain number be too difficult to see, note down what you perceive.
{{Blurimage|file=colorblind1.jpg|caption=Please state the numbers you see and the ones you cannot identify internally.|align=center}}
The test is administered in order to determine whether you suffer from Pigment Loss caused by extensive exposure to <span style="color:#fff212;">Level 142</span> and Color Therapy. The results might suggest an impairment in the ability to recognize color contrast and meaning when using fluorescent light. Should you fail to see a certain amount of numbers on the test, you will be immediately reclassified and will need to undergo treatment in Color Therapy.

'''Do not try again after undergoing treatment.''' This practice will accelerate instability in perception. 

Thank You.</div>
