<div class="titleblock"><span class="titlebox">COLOR THERAPY</span><br><center>“Every Color Has A Purpose.”</center><br>

<center><code>[PLEASE READ]</code></center>
<span style="
   background: linear-gradient(to right, rgba(0,0,0,0), rgba(255,255,255,1));
     -webkit-background-clip: text;
     -webkit-text-fill-color;
     -moz-background-clip: text;
     -moz-text-fill-color;">{{blurimage|file=colortherapy1.jpg|caption=First ever image taken of Color Therapy in Level 142. Photograph status alive.|align=center}}Color Therapy is the name of the secondary recreational area that is sometimes found as an offshoot from the main area of <span style="color:#00a859;">Level 142</span>, particularly following extensive time of play or during times where one lone wanderer is waiting for more players to join. These areas can be compared to abandoned children's therapy rooms, indoor playgrounds, or early educational centers quipped with large crayons, geometric shapes with padded interiors, foam floors, and colorful educational equipment.  


While the initial feeling upon entering Color Therapy is a sense of safety, this particular location has been tied directly to rapid mental deterioration as well as the manifestation of Pigment Loss. Wanderers often experience calmness, fatigue, and decreased levels of anxiety when in these rooms for extended amounts of time.

Objects found in Color Therapy relate directly to pigments whose identification is problematic for those affected by Pigment Loss. Should wanderers struggle to recognize any particular color, they will start to see irregularities occurring only on those objects that pertain to the aforementioned pigment. As evidenced in cases of blue recognition difficulties, blue crayons disappeared from drawers, blue foam blocks started looking squashed or far away, and circles with blue coloring had significantly greater chances of turning into Soft Spots.

It appears that the interiors exacerbate the effects of the pigment loss due to extended stay in Color Therapy. Some survivors have claimed seeing colors looking faded, wrongly classified, or not being visible at all. Moreover, a number of accounts stated that colors started bleeding into adjacent areas, causing visual disorientation in recognizing safe circles during subsequent rounds. There are no known instances of any escape from Color Therapy. Nevertheless, it was observed that all rooms eventually return to the arena of <span style="color:#ed3237;">Level 142</span>.
==Learn More==
<div class="tabs">
<ul class="tabs__caption">
<li class="active">Object-Correlation Anomaly (Color Dependency Index)</li>
<li>Shared Perception Divergence</li>
</ul>
<div class="tabs__content active">All objects in the Color Therapy rooms shows a dependence on the full functioning color spectrum range of the observer, a phenomenon referred to as the Object-Correlation Anomaly. What is implied by this is that objects do not have a stable quality but rather one which depends on their recognition and classification as objects based on their colors.


With increasing stages of Pigment Loss in a person, object that belong to the same color range start deteriorating perceptually. Physical function remains unaffected; however, this process leads to a decrease in perceptual clarity incorrect boundary recognition, and perceptual dropout where the object appears to be partly there or nowhere at all at some instances. 

At the higher stages of the illness, whole classes of objects whose pigments are no longer available to the person become invisible to his eyes although physically they remain there in the chamber. 

The items most commonly affected are usually those that depend on color the most: crayons, foam constructions, geometric arrangements, etc. The moment when a wanderer stops recognizing any particular pigment results in the gradual elimination of that item from one's perception, first by means of flattening and subsequent desaturation and ultimately by omitting its existence. 

One should point out that unaffected wanderers may still see those items normally. {{Blurimage|file=colortest1.jpg|caption=What colors do you see? Photographer status deceased.|align=center}} </div>
<div class="tabs__content">Color Therapy displays a consistent phenomenon of multi-perceiver desynchronization known as Shared Perception Divergence. This phenomenon involves the occurrence of various visual interpretations of the same physical setting amongst several wanderers at any time.


In regular circumstances, slight various in color intensity and object clarity occur between perceivers. But the presence of just one person suffering from Pigment Loss greatly increases the extent of divergence experienced. As such, each perceiver sees separate sets of circles colored differently, with objects placed in completely different locations and environmental demarcation lines being altered accordingly.

The disagreement between perceivers as to whether Soft Spots exist or where they as well as whether they can be moved around, has been a very common issue. For instance, in an encounter, while one perceiver saw a safe path to follow, another saw it completely covered o filled with Soft Spots. Such disagreements usually culminate in life-threatening 
confusion in transition phases of <span style="color:#fff212;">Level 142</span> matches. 

In cases where divergence has progressed to its advanced phase, there will be an ultimate collapse of any semblance of consensus reality with the rooms. In such instances, there can be a situation where it is not possible for the wanderer to confirm whether one is dealing with the same physical reality, leading to individual perception of reality within one room. {{Blurimage|file=colorblind2.webp|caption=You Will Adjust.|align=center}} </div>
</div>
</span></div>
==<span style="color:#fff212;">Colonies & Outposts</span>==
<span style="color:#FFFFFF;>There have been no reported colonies or settlements established in <span style="color:#fff212;">Level 142</span>. 

Attempts at forming temporary resting formations and coordinating observation cycles have all proved futile because of the nature of the match-based system in the level. When there are enough wanderers, the room will force itself and the wanderers into gameplay despite any intentions that may arise from outside. All attempts at mapping the area have resulted in the parties becoming part of the game cycles instead. It is typical for wanderers to temporarily band together and work as a team while they are in a game scenario, but such social ties rarely last long. </span>
==<span style="color:#fff212;">Entities</span>==
{{blurimage|file=twister1.jpg|caption=Recent image taken of Level 142. Photographer status unknown.|align=left}}
<span style="color:#FFFFFF;><span style="color:#ed3237;">Level 142</span> contains no entities. 

It is worth saying that the Twister spinner is in control of the system itself as a core of all actions in the level. The behavior of the spinner, as well as its voice, is widely regarded as the only intelligent or semi-intelligent thing that can be seen. The spinner usually intensifies challenges at later matches. Such challenges imply a rapid issue of commands, a more complex body positioning task, and some deviation from fairness and randomness in choosing positions. It has been noted that the spinner begins to choose those positions that make wanderers unstable or force them to perform physically impossible postures. Moreover, there are no other creatures or anomalies in the level. 

However, winners who make it out alive may see colored circles in any Backrooms level, hear voices of people who do not really exist, and hear distorted laughter. </span>
