==<span style="color:#fff212;">Description</span>==
<span style="color:#00afef;"><span style="color:#00a859;">Level 142.1</span> is thought to be an offshoot layer stemming from <span style="color:#ed3237;">[[Level 142]]</span>, in contrast to <span style="color:#FFFFFF;">[[Level 142]]</span>'s game-like setting and Twister theme. <span style="color:#fff212;">Level 142.1</span> is less organized, less of a game, and very much unfinished. 

Reports of documentation are few due to difficult or rare entrances and an extremely high degree of memory alteration among witnesses. 

The area seems similar to the pristine white chamber filled with colored circles that resemble those seen in <span style="color:#00afef;"><span style="color:#00a859;">[[Level 142]]</span>. These dots are all different in size and location and follow no pattern whatsoever. They can appear on any surface without discrimination: walls, floors, ceilings, objects, even living things. In almost all cases, there is always one central structure resembling a flower, an anatomical mode of plastic or broken playground equipment.

<span style="color:#00afef;">Lighting conditions do not change; there are neither shadows nor any source of light aside from the fluorescent lights on the ceiling that provide a constant stream of hums just like those in <span style="color:#ed3237;">[[Level 142]]</span>, although the one from this sublevel is quieter and deeper. 

Audio recordings taken in the room tend to degrade into overlapping children's voices after a while, even though they cannot be heard at the moment. 

People who get trapped in the room often notice the urge to touch colored dots. The more one approaches the central structure, the stronger the urge. The sensation when the dots are touched differs from person to person; most people perceive them as painted spots, yet some feel them to be warm, rubbery, or even “breathing” in their hands.  {{blurimage|file=sublayer142.jpg|caption=Rare image taken of Level 142.1. Photographer status dead.|align=center}} <span style="color:#00afef;">The room is not large in size, but it appears impossible to map out. Some corridors occasionally pop up where the walls used to be. They have the same style as the white, fluorescent lighting and colored dots. However, the hallways will end up connecting back to the room again. The position and quantity of flowers may change every time a wanderer returns to <span style="color:#00afef;">Level 142.1</span>. 

The exits vary to different people. Those who were able to find their way out stated that they eventually found themselves inside <span style="color:#fff212;">Level 142</SPAN> again, but this time they were lying down on several colored dots as though they were still playing the game. </SPAN>
<tabber>
|-| Pigment Loss=

<span style="color:#fff212;"><span style="color:#ed3237;">Pigment Loss</span> is a verified cognitive effect which arises due to long-term exposure to <span style="color:#00a859;">Level 142.1</span>.

<span style="color:#ed3237;">Pigment Loss</span> occurs in a slower manner, initially manifesting itself as a wanderer's inability to recognize one particular color among all other circles in the environment. While in most cases, the lost color was blue or purple, no distinct pattern was determined yet. 

The early stages of Pigment Loss are characterized by difficulty recognizing colors verbally, headaches resulting from fluorescent lights, and claims that dots seem to be "empty" or "washed out". </span>

<span style="color:#fff212;">The subsequent stages involve the total disappearance of a specific color from the consciousness of the wanderer; previously colored objects turn white, gray, or even transparent. Those suffering from <span style="color:#ed3237;">Pigment Loss</span> tend to feel distressed when communicating with normal wanderers, especially in conversations where the topic is color-related navigation. They may try to overcome their loss by memorizing the locations of dots instead of the colors themselves. However, this tendency never lasts more than several hours, as spatial awareness seems to be damaged as well. Advanced cases include a more pronounced fading of colors. </span>

<span style="color:#fff212;">According to wanderers' testimonies, some even become color blind. There is no known cure. Some survivors swear that <span style="color:#ed3237;">Pigment Loss</span> does not disappear entirely after leaving the level. One wanderer refused to accept reality and kept claiming that the sky used to be brighter.</span>

